.TH WEBSOCKET_NEXT_EVENT 3 "2026-06-24" "libhttp2 0.1.0" "libhttp2 Programmer's Manual"
.SH NAME
websocket_next_event \- retrieve next protocol event from the context's queue (plumbing model)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include <websocket.h>
#include <protocol_events.h>

int websocket_next_event(websocket_ctx_t *ctx, protocol_event_t *event);
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
Dequeues the next event (if any) into the caller-provided \fBevent\fP structure and returns 1. Returns 0 if the queue is empty or on invalid arguments (NULL ctx or event).

Events are of type \fBprotocol_event_type_t\fP (WS_EVENT_TEXT, WS_EVENT_BINARY, WS_EVENT_PING, WS_EVENT_PONG, WS_EVENT_CLOSE, WS_EVENT_ERROR, ...). The \fBu.ws_message\fP or \fBu.ws_close\fP union member provides access to \fBconst uint8_t *data; size_t len;\fP (pointers are valid only until the next \fBfeed_input\fP or \fBdestroy\fP call — unencapsulated data per ADR 006).

This is the primary mechanism for receiving parsed protocol data without the library performing actions.
.SH RETURN VALUES
1 if an event was copied into *event, 0 otherwise.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
protocol_event_t ev;
while (websocket_next_event(ws, &ev)) {
    if (ev.type == WS_EVENT_TEXT) {
        /* process ev.u.ws_message.data, len */
    } else if (ev.type == WS_EVENT_ERROR) { ... }
}
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
websocket_create(3), websocket_feed_input(3), protocol_event_t(3), libhttp2(3)
.SH NOTES
Queue size is set at creation. When full, further input may drop events (see enqueue logic). Caller owns interpretation and any responses.